-- ─── PATHWAY 1: Technical QS Practice ─────────────────────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Introduction to Quantity Surveying
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Introduction to Quantity Surveying\n\nQuantity surveying is the **financial management of construction projects**. As a QS, you control costs, manage contracts, and ensure projects deliver value for money.\n\n---\n\n### What Does a QS Do?\n\n| Function | Description | Typical Output |\n|----------|-------------|----------------|\n| Cost Estimating | Predicting project costs | Cost plans, budgets |\n| Measurement | Quantifying building works | Bill of quantities |\n| Procurement | Selecting contractors | Tender documents |\n| Contract Admin | Managing contracts | Payment certificates |\n| Valuation | Assessing work value | Interim valuations |\n\n### The QS in Nigerian Construction\n\nIn Nigeria, quantity surveyors work across:\n- **Consultancy firms** — Providing cost advice to clients\n- **Contractors** — Managing commercial operations on site\n- **Government** — Public sector procurement and audit\n- **Real estate** — Development appraisal and valuation\n\n### Career Progression\n\n```\nGraduate QS (0-2 yrs) → Assistant QS → Project QS → Senior QS → Principal QS → Partner/Director\n```\n\n### Key Skills\n\n1. **Numerical accuracy** — Every measurement matters\n2. **Attention to detail** — Missing items cost millions of Naira\n3. **Communication** — Explain costs to non-technical stakeholders\n4. **Commercial awareness** — Understand market dynamics\n5. **Technology** — Master digital measurement tools\n\n> **Nigerian Context**: The QS profession is regulated by QSRBN (Quantity Surveyors Registration Board of Nigeria) and supported by NIQS (Nigerian Institute of Quantity Surveyors). Registration is mandatory for practice.\n\n### Professional Bodies\n\n| Body | Role | Membership Grades |\n|------|------|-------------------|\n| NIQS | Professional institute | Student → Technician → Graduate → Associate → Member → Fellow |\n| QSRBN | Statutory regulator | Registration required for practice |\n| RICS | International recognition | APC pathway to MRICS |\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- QS is a rewarding career with strong demand in Nigeria\n- Professional registration (NIQS/QSRBN) is essential\n- Continuous learning is required throughout your career\n- Technology is transforming how QS professionals work' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Construction Drawings & Specifications
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Construction Drawings & Specifications\n\nReading construction drawings is a **fundamental skill** for every quantity surveyor. This module covers the essential elements you need to understand.\n\n---\n\n### Types of Drawings\n\n| Drawing Type | Purpose | Key Information |\n|-------------|---------|------------------|\n| Architectural | Design intent, layout | Floor plans, elevations, sections |\n| Structural | Load-bearing elements | Foundations, beams, columns, slabs |\n| M&E | Services | Plumbing, electrical, HVAC |\n| Civil | External works | Site plans, drainage layouts |\n\n### Drawing Scales\n\n| Scale | Use Case |\n|-------|----------|\n| 1:50 | Floor plans, elevations |\n| 1:100 | Site plans, roof plans |\n| 1:20 | Sections, details |\n| 1:5 | Construction details |\n\n### Reading a Floor Plan — Step by Step\n\n1. **Identify grid lines** and overall dimensions\n2. **Locate rooms** and their dimensions\n3. **Check door and window** positions and sizes\n4. **Note wall thicknesses** (225mm external, 115mm internal)\n5. **Identify finishes** from the schedule\n6. **Check levels** — FFL, GL, ceiling heights\n\n### Common Abbreviations\n\n| Abbreviation | Meaning |\n|-------------|----------|\n| CL | Centre Line |\n| FFL | Finished Floor Level |\n| GL | Ground Level |\n| RC | Reinforced Concrete |\n| WC | Water Closet |\n| BS | British Standard |\n\n### Nigerian Drawing Conventions\n\n- **Dimensions**: Always in millimetres\n- **Levels**: Measured from a datum (usually ground floor = 0.000)\n- **Wall types**: Sandcrete blocks specified by thickness\n- **Materials**: Local materials indicated in notes\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Always check the drawing date and revision number. Using outdated drawings is a costly mistake that can run into millions of Naira.\n\n### Practice Exercise\n\nTake a simple residential drawing and identify:\n1. All room dimensions and areas\n2. Door and window sizes from the schedule\n3. Wall thicknesses (external vs internal)\n4. Foundation type from structural drawings\n5. Roof slope from sections' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: SMM7 Measurement Rules
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## SMM7 Measurement Rules\n\nThe **Standard Method of Measurement 7th Edition (SMM7)** is the most widely used measurement standard in Nigerian quantity surveying practice.\n\n---\n\n### When Does SMM7 Apply?\n\n- Building works (residential, commercial, institutional)\n- JCT contracts and many bespoke Nigerian contracts\n- Insurance reinstatement valuations\n\n### Basic Rules for Taking-Off\n\n1. **Order of Taking-Off**: Site preparation → Substructure → Superstructure → Finishes → Roofing → Drainage\n2. **Dimensions**: Always in metres (m)\n3. **Description**: Follow SMM7 rules strictly\n4. **Waste Allowance**: Included in rates unless stated otherwise\n5. **Minimum Dimensions**: Generally 100mm or larger\n\n### Common Measurement Units\n\n| Item | Unit | Example |\n|------|------|----------|\n| Excavation | m³ | Excavate trench 1.2m deep |\n| Concrete | m³ | RC foundation concrete 1:2:4 |\n| Blockwork | m² | 225mm thick block wall |\n| Plastering | m² | 15mm cement plaster both sides |\n| Roofing | m² | Galvanised roofing sheets |\n| Doors/Windows | nr | Flush door 44mm thick |\n\n### Description Writing Rules\n\nEach description must include:\n- **Material** — What it''s made of\n- **Thickness/Size** — Dimensions\n- **Type** — Specific classification\n- **Workmanship** — Quality standard\n\n**Example**: "225mm thick sandcrete blockwall in cement mortar 1:6, including vertical reinforced concrete columns at 3m centres"\n\n### Nigerian Adaptations\n\n- NSMM (Nigerian Standard Method of Measurement) supplements\n- Local material specifications (sandcrete blocks, local timber)\n- Nigerian labour rates and overheads\n- Federal Ministry of Works adaptations for civil works\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- SMM7 is the foundation of measurement practice\n- Consistency is key — always follow the same approach\n- Practice with real drawings to build competence\n- Keep a copy of SMM7 on your desk at all times' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Taking-Off Practice (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Taking-Off Practice — Exercise\n\nThis exercise provides hands-on practice in taking-off quantities from drawings using SMM7 rules.\n\n---\n\n### Exercise 1: Foundation Taking-Off\n\n**Given**: A simple residential building with the following dimensions:\n- Overall: 12m × 8m\n- Foundation width: 900mm\n- Foundation depth: 1.2m\n- Blinding thickness: 50mm\n- Foundation concrete: 1:2:4, 300mm thick\n\n**Tasks**:\n1. Measure the excavation volume\n2. Measure the blinding concrete\n3. Measure the foundation concrete\n4. Allow for backfilling\n\n### Solution Approach\n\n**Step 1: Centre Line Length**\n- External perimeter = 2(12 + 8) = 40m\n- Centre line = 40 - 4(0.225) = 39.1m (for 225mm walls)\n\n**Step 2: Excavation**\n- Length: 39.1m (centre line)\n- Width: 0.9m\n- Depth: 1.2m\n- Volume = 39.1 × 0.9 × 1.2 = **42.23 m³**\n\n**Step 3: Blinding**\n- Length: 39.1m\n- Width: 0.9m\n- Thickness: 0.05m\n- Volume = 39.1 × 0.9 × 0.05 = **1.76 m³**\n\n**Step 4: Foundation Concrete**\n- Length: 39.1m\n- Width: 0.6m (foundation width less blinding)\n- Thickness: 0.3m\n- Volume = 39.1 × 0.6 × 0.3 = **7.04 m³**\n\n**Step 5: Backfilling**\n- Excavation volume - Blinding - Foundation concrete\n- 42.23 - 1.76 - 7.04 = **33.43 m³**\n\n### Exercise 2: Blockwork Taking-Off\n\n**Given**: External wall, 12m long, 3m high, 225mm thick\n- 3 window openings: 1.2m × 1.5m each\n- 1 door opening: 0.9m × 2.1m\n\n**Tasks**:\n1. Calculate gross wall area\n2. Calculate deductions\n3. Calculate net blockwork area\n\n### Self-Assessment Checklist\n\n- [ ] Did you use centre line measurements for walls?\n- [ ] Did you deduct openings over 0.3 m²?\n- [ ] Did you include working space allowance?\n- [ ] Are your descriptions complete per SMM7?\n- [ ] Did you check arithmetic?' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 1: BOQ Preparation & Pricing
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Bill of Quantities Preparation & Pricing\n\nThe BOQ is the **most important document** in traditional procurement. This module covers the complete workflow.\n\n---\n\n### BOQ Structure\n\n1. **Preliminaries (Section A)** — Site establishment, temporary works, H&S\n2. **Measured Works (Section B)** — Substructure, superstructure, finishes, M&E\n3. **Provisional Sums (Section C)** — Contingencies, specialist work\n4. **Prime Cost Sums (Section D)** — Client-nominated subcontractors\n\n### Preliminaries Section\n\n| Item | Description | Unit |\n|------|-------------|------|\n| A1.1 | Site establishment and offices | LS |\n| A2.1 | Scaffolding | m² |\n| A2.2 | Temporary power supply | LS |\n| A3.1 | Health and safety | LS |\n| A4.1 | Insurance | LS |\n\n### Rate Build-Up\n\n**Ceramic Floor Tiling (per m²):**\n\n| Component | Cost (₦) |\n|-----------|----------|\n| Tiles | 2,500 |\n| Adhesive | 800 |\n| Grout | 300 |\n| Labour (tiler) | 1,200 |\n| Labour (helper) | 400 |\n| Overheads (10%) | 520 |\n| Profit (10%) | 520 |\n| **Total** | **5,740** |\n\n### Nigerian BOQ Considerations\n\n1. **Local Materials**: Specify Nigerian blocks, cement, etc.\n2. **Naira Pricing**: All rates in Naira\n3. **VAT**: Include 7.5% VAT where applicable\n4. **Withholding Tax**: 5% on payments to contractors\n\n### Common Errors\n\n1. Missing items — incomplete measurement\n2. Wrong units — m³ vs m² confusion\n3. Duplicate items — same item measured twice\n4. Incorrect rates — outdated pricing\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Use a checklist to ensure completeness. A missing item in the BOQ can cost millions in variations.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: Rate Analysis & Build-Up
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Rate Analysis & Build-Up\n\nDeveloping accurate rate analyses is essential for competitive and profitable pricing.\n\n---\n\n### Rate Components\n\nEvery rate must include:\n1. **Materials** — Cost of raw materials\n2. **Labour** — Worker wages and productivity\n3. **Plant/Equipment** — Machinery costs\n4. **Overheads** — Site and head office costs\n5. **Profit** — Business margin\n\n### Material Consumption Rates\n\n| Item | Unit | Consumption |\n|------|------|-------------|\n| Cement (50kg bag) | m³ concrete | 6-7 bags |\n| Sharp sand | m³ concrete | 0.7-0.8 m³ |\n| Granite (20mm) | m³ concrete | 1.4-1.5 m³ |\n| Blocks (9-inch) | m² wall | 10 blocks |\n| Blocks (6-inch) | m² wall | 12.5 blocks |\n\n### Labour Productivity (Nigeria)\n\n| Trade | Output/Day | Daily Rate (₦) |\n|-------|-----------|----------------|\n| Block layer | 100-150 blocks | 5,000-7,000 |\n| Helper | — | 3,000-4,000 |\n| Carpenter | — | 6,000-8,000 |\n| Steel fixer | — | 5,000-7,000 |\n| Tiler | 8-12 m² | 6,000-8,000 |\n\n### Current Material Prices (2024)\n\n| Material | Unit | Price Range (₦) |\n|----------|------|------------------|\n| Cement (50kg) | bag | 5,500-7,000 |\n| Sharp sand | m³ | 8,000-15,000 |\n| Granite (20mm) | m³ | 35,000-55,000 |\n| 9-inch block | nr | 500-700 |\n| Reinforcement (12mm) | kg | 880-1,050 |\n\n### Example Rate Build-Up: Blockwork\n\n**9-inch blockwall per m²:**\n\n| Component | Calculation | Cost (₦) |\n|-----------|-------------|----------|\n| Blocks | 10 × ₦600 | 6,000 |\n| Mortar | 0.05 m³ × ₦45,000 | 2,250 |\n| Labour | 0.5 day × ₦6,000 | 3,000 |\n| **Subtotal** | | 11,250 |\n| Overheads (12%) | | 1,350 |\n| Profit (10%) | | 1,125 |\n| **Total Rate** | | **13,725** |\n\n> **Nigerian Context**: Rates vary significantly by location. Lagos and Abuja rates are typically 15-25% higher than other states. Always research local prices.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Advanced Measurement Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Advanced Measurement Case Study\n\n### Project: 3-Storey Commercial Office Building, Lagos\n\n**Scope**: Prepare a complete measurement and BOQ for the building works.\n\n---\n\n### Project Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Building type | Office (Grade A) |\n| Floors | 3 + basement parking |\n| Floor area | 2,400 m² (800 m² per floor) |\n| Structure | RC frame with sandcrete block infill |\n| Foundation | Pad foundations on laterite |\n| Roof | Reinforced concrete flat roof |\n\n### Measurement Approach\n\n**Phase 1: Substructure**\n1. Excavate for pad foundations\n2. Blinding concrete 1:3:6\n3. RC foundation concrete 1:2:4\n4. Ground floor slab on grade\n5. Backfill and compact\n\n**Phase 2: Superstructure**\n1. RC columns (225×225mm and 300×300mm)\n2. RC beams and slabs\n3. Blockwork infill walls (225mm external, 115mm internal)\n4. Staircase construction\n\n**Phase 3: Finishes**\n1. Floor finishes — granite tiles (public), ceramic tiles (offices)\n2. Wall finishes — emulsion paint, some with tiling\n3. Ceiling — suspended ceiling in offices, POP in reception\n4. External — aluminium cladding, glazing\n\n### Key Measurement Challenges\n\n1. **Complex column grid** — Varying column sizes require separate measurement\n2. **Service risers** — Dedicated measurement for M&E risers\n3. **Basement parking** — Include waterproofing, drainage, line marking\n4. **Glazing system** — Curtain walling measured by area and type\n\n### Value Engineering Opportunities\n\n| Element | Original Spec | VE Alternative | Savings |\n|---------|---------------|----------------|----------|\n| Floor tiles | Italian granite | Local granite | 35% |\n| Ceiling | Full suspended | Partial POP | 20% |\n| Paint | Dulux | Complementary brand | 15% |\n| Glazing | Double glazed | High-performance single | 25% |\n\n### Deliverables\n\n- Complete taking-off sheets\n- Bill of quantities (Nigerian format)\n- Preliminaries schedule\n- Rate analysis for key items\n- Cost summary by element' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Value Engineering Techniques
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Value Engineering Techniques\n\nValue engineering systematically improves the **value-to-cost ratio** of construction projects without compromising quality.\n\n---\n\n### What is Value Engineering?\n\n**Value = Function ÷ Cost**\n\nVE is NOT about cutting costs — it''s about optimising what you get for every Naira spent.\n\n### The VE Job Plan\n\n1. **Information Phase** — Gather all project data\n2. **Function Analysis** — What does each element do?\n3. **Creative Phase** — Generate alternatives\n4. **Evaluation Phase** — Assess alternatives\n5. **Development Phase** — Refine best options\n6. **Presentation Phase** — Report to client\n\n### Common VE Opportunities in Nigeria\n\n| Element | Standard Spec | VE Alternative | Saving |\n|---------|---------------|----------------|--------|\n| External walls | 225mm blocks | 150mm + insulation | 12-18% |\n| Roofing | Stone-coated tiles | Long-span aluminium | 30-40% |\n| Floor finishes | Imported granite | Local granite/marble | 25-35% |\n| Painting | 3-coat gloss | 2-coat textcoat | 15-20% |\n| M&E | VRF system | Split units | 20-30% |\n\n### VE Case Study\n\n**Project**: 50-unit residential estate, Abuja\n**Budget**: ₦2.5 billion\n**VE Savings Achieved**: ₦375 million (15%)\n\n**Key Changes**:\n1. Replaced imported tiles with local alternatives (₦85M saved)\n2. Optimised structural design — reduced reinforcement by 8% (₦120M saved)\n3. Simplified M&E specification (₦95M saved)\n4. Revised preliminaries based on realistic programme (₦75M saved)\n\n### When to Apply VE\n\n- **Stage 1-2**: Maximum impact (concept/scheme design)\n- **Stage 3**: Moderate impact (detailed design)\n- **Stage 4**: Limited impact (construction)\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The earlier VE is applied, the greater the savings potential. By construction stage, most costs are fixed.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Cost Planning & Control
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Cost Planning & Control\n\nEffective cost management ensures projects are delivered **within budget** while maintaining quality.\n\n---\n\n### Elemental Cost Planning\n\n| Element | Typical % of Total Cost |\n|---------|--------------------------|\n| Substructure | 8-12% |\n| Superstructure (walls) | 12-18% |\n| Superstructure (roof) | 8-12% |\n| Finishes | 15-22% |\n| Services (M&E) | 25-35% |\n| External Works | 5-8% |\n| Preliminaries | 10-15% |\n\n### Cost Plan Stages\n\n1. **Strategic Cost Plan** — Budget setting (concept phase)\n2. **Outline Cost Plan** — Elemental estimating (scheme design)\n3. **Detailed Cost Plan** — Quantified estimating (developed design)\n4. **Final Cost Plan** — Full measurement (technical design)\n\n### Cost Control Methods\n\n1. **Monthly Cost Reports** — Actual vs budget comparison\n2. **Forecast to Completion** — Revised estimates\n3. **Variance Analysis** — Identify deviations\n4. **Change Control** — Manage scope changes\n5. **Cash Flow Projections** — Monthly expenditure planning\n\n### Cost Report Template\n\n| Item | Budget (₦) | Committed (₦) | Actual (₦) | Forecast (₦) | Variance (₦) |\n|------|-----------|---------------|-----------|-------------|-------------|\n| Substructure | 250M | 240M | 235M | 248M | +2M |\n| Superstructure | 800M | 650M | 420M | 810M | -10M |\n| Finishes | 450M | 0 | 0 | 460M | -10M |\n\n### Nigerian Cost Data Sources\n\n1. BCIS (Building Cost Information Service)\n2. QS annual cost guides\n3. Market research — local price surveys\n4. Historical project records\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Build a database of completed projects. Historical cost data is invaluable for future estimates.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 4, Module 3: Consultancy Practice Simulation (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Consultancy Practice Simulation\n\nThis exercise simulates a **real consultancy engagement** from inception to completion.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Client**: Dangote Industries Ltd\n**Project**: New 5-storey office headquarters, Ikoyi, Lagos\n**Budget**: ₦8 billion\n**Your Role**: Lead Quantity Surveyor\n\n### Phase 1: Feasibility (Week 1-2)\n\n**Tasks**:\n1. Prepare an order of cost estimate using area-based method\n2. Review site constraints and access\n3. Identify potential VE opportunities\n4. Present initial budget to client\n\n**Deliverable**: Feasibility report with cost estimate (±25% accuracy)\n\n### Phase 2: Cost Planning (Week 3-6)\n\n**Tasks**:\n1. Develop elemental cost plan from design team information\n2. Set cost limits per element\n3. Prepare procurement strategy\n4. Draft tender documentation\n\n**Deliverable**: Detailed cost plan and tender documents\n\n### Phase 3: Procurement (Week 7-10)\n\n**Tasks**:\n1. Pre-qualify contractors (minimum 5)\n2. Issue tender documents\n3. Analyse tender returns\n4. Prepare tender report with recommendations\n\n**Deliverable**: Tender report and contract award recommendation\n\n### Phase 4: Contract Administration (Week 11-52)\n\n**Tasks**:\n1. Process interim payment certificates\n2. Manage variations\n3. Monitor cost against budget\n4. Prepare monthly cost reports\n5. Assess claims\n\n**Deliverable**: Monthly cost reports, payment certificates, variation orders\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight | Excellent |\n|-----------|--------|----------|\n| Accuracy of measurements | 25% | Within 2% of check measurement |\n| Rate competitiveness | 20% | Within 5% of market rates |\n| BOQ completeness | 25% | No missing items |\n| Professional presentation | 15% | Clear, well-organized |\n| Commercial awareness | 15% | Realistic contingencies |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 5, Module 1: Strategic Advisory & Leadership
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Strategic Advisory & Leadership\n\nAt the senior level, QS professionals provide **strategic cost advice** and lead teams.\n\n---\n\n### Strategic Cost Advisory\n\n**Types of Advisory**:\n- Investment appraisal and feasibility\n- Procurement strategy\n- Risk allocation advice\n- Whole-life costing\n- Capital expenditure planning\n\n### Leadership Skills for QS Professionals\n\n1. **Team Management** — Delegation, motivation, performance\n2. **Client Relationship** — Trust, communication, expectation management\n3. **Business Development** — Winning work, networking, reputation\n4. **Strategic Thinking** — Long-term planning, market positioning\n\n### Expert Witness Role\n\n**When Called Upon**:\n- Construction disputes and arbitration\n- Insurance claims\n- Compulsory acquisition\n- Professional negligence cases\n\n**Requirements**:\n- Impartial and objective\n- Evidence-based opinions\n- Clear, professional reports\n- Court/arbitration presentation skills\n\n### Firm Leadership\n\n**Key Responsibilities**:\n- Setting strategic direction\n- Managing P&L\n- Developing talent\n- Building client base\n- Quality assurance\n\n> **Pro Tip**: At this level, your reputation is your most valuable asset. Every engagement builds or diminishes it.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: Complex Dispute Resolution (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Complex Dispute Resolution — Case Study\n\n### Project: Lagos-Ibadan Expressway Rehabilitation\n**Claim Value**: ₦4.2 billion\n**Your Role**: Quantum Expert\n\n---\n\n### Background\n\nThe contractor claims additional costs due to:\n1. Unforeseen ground conditions (rock excavation)\n2. Client-caused delays (late access to site)\n3. Variation orders (scope changes)\n4. Escalation of material prices\n\n### Analysis Framework\n\n**Step 1: Entitlement Analysis**\n- Review contract terms (FIDIC Red Book)\n- Identify qualifying events\n- Assess time bar provisions\n\n**Step 2: Quantum Analysis**\n\n| Claim Element | Contractor Claim (₦) | Expert Assessment (₦) | Basis |\n|---------------|----------------------|----------------------|-------|\n| Rock excavation | 1,200M | 850M | Actual vs claimed rates |\n| Delay costs | 1,500M | 980M | Programme analysis |\n| Variations | 800M | 720M | Pricing verification |\n| Escalation | 700M | 450M | Market data analysis |\n| **Total** | **4,200M** | **3,000M** | |\n\n**Step 3: Programme Analysis**\n- As-planned vs as-built comparison\n- Critical path impact assessment\n- Delay attribution\n\n**Step 4: Expert Report**\n- Executive summary\n- Terms of reference\n- Assumptions and qualifications\n- Detailed analysis\n- Conclusions and recommendations\n\n### Key Lessons\n\n1. **Documentation is king** — Contemporaneous records win disputes\n2. **Impartiality** — Expert duty is to the tribunal, not the instructing party\n3. **Proportionality** — Analysis must match the claim value\n4. **Clarity** — Reports must be understood by non-technical tribunal members' WHERE pathway_slug = 'technical-qs-practice' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

-- ─── PATHWAY 2: Construction Commercial Management ────────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Commercial Basics for QS
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Commercial Basics for QS\n\nCommercial management is the **engine room** of construction profitability.\n\n---\n\n### What is Commercial Management?\n\nManaging the financial and contractual aspects of construction projects to ensure profitability and value for money.\n\n### Key Commercial Functions\n\n1. **Cost Control** — Monitoring expenditure against budget\n2. **Revenue Management** — Maximising income through claims and variations\n3. **Risk Management** — Identifying and mitigating financial risks\n4. **Cash Flow Management** — Ensuring positive project cash flow\n5. **Contract Management** — Administering contractual obligations\n\n### The Commercial Cycle\n\n```\nEstimate → Tender → Contract → Execute → Control → Settle → Learn\n```\n\n### Contractor''s Perspective\n\n| Phase | Commercial Activity |\n|-------|-------------------|\n| Pre-contract | Estimating, tendering, risk assessment |\n| Contract award | Subcontracting, procurement |\n| Execution | Valuations, variations, claims |\n| Completion | Final account, defects liability |\n\n### Profit and Loss\n\n| P&L Element | Target % |\n|-------------|----------|\n| Revenue | 100% |\n| Direct costs | -70-80% |\n| Gross margin | 20-30% |\n| Overheads | -8-12% |\n| Net profit | 5-10% |\n\n> **Nigerian Context**: Profit margins in Nigerian construction are typically 5-10%. Effective commercial management is the difference between profit and loss.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Contract Administration Intro
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Contract Administration Introduction\n\nContract administration ensures all parties fulfill their **contractual obligations**.\n\n---\n\n### The Contract Administrator\n\n**Role**: impartial administrator ensuring contract compliance\n\n**Key Responsibilities**:\n1. Issue instructions and directions\n2. Assess and certify payments\n3. Manage variations\n4. Monitor programme\n5. Issue completion certificates\n\n### Payment Administration\n\n| Step | Action | Timeline |\n|------|--------|----------|\n| 1 | Contractor submits application | Monthly |\n| 2 | QS reviews and assesses | 7 days |\n| 3 | Payment certificate issued | 14 days |\n| 4 | Client makes payment | 14-28 days |\n\n### Variation Management\n\n**Types**:\n- **Additions** — New work required\n- **Omissions** — Work removed\n- **Modifications** — Changes to existing work\n\n**Procedure**:\n1. Instruction issued\n2. Contractor provides quotation\n3. QS assesses and negotiates\n4. Variation order issued\n\n### Record Keeping\n\nEssential records:\n- Site diary\n- Payment records\n- Correspondence\n- Programme updates\n- Photographic evidence\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Document everything in writing. Verbal instructions lead to disputes.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: Cost Estimation Methods
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Cost Estimation Methods\n\nAccurate cost estimation is the foundation of **commercial success**.\n\n---\n\n### Estimation Methods\n\n| Method | Stage | Accuracy | Input Required |\n|--------|-------|----------|----------------|\n| Area-based | Feasibility | ±25-35% | Floor area, building type |\n| Elemental | Outline design | ±15-25% | Element quantities |\n| Unit rate | Detailed design | ±10-15% | Measured quantities |\n| Comprehensive | Tender | ±5-10% | Full BOQ |\n\n### Area-Based Estimating\n\n**Formula**: Cost = Floor Area × Cost per m²\n\n**Nigerian Rates (2024)**:\n\n| Building Type | Cost/m² (₦) |\n|---------------|-------------|\n| Residential (basic) | 250,000-350,000 |\n| Residential (medium) | 350,000-500,000 |\n| Residential (high-end) | 500,000-800,000 |\n| Office (standard) | 350,000-500,000 |\n| Office (Grade A) | 500,000-750,000 |\n| Retail | 300,000-450,000 |\n| Hotel | 400,000-650,000 |\n\n### Elemental Estimating\n\nBreak costs into functional elements:\n\n| Element | Residential % | Office % |\n|---------|--------------|----------|\n| Substructure | 10% | 8% |\n| Superstructure | 25% | 22% |\n| Finishes | 20% | 18% |\n| M&E Services | 25% | 35% |\n| Preliminaries | 12% | 12% |\n| External works | 8% | 5% |\n\n### Contingency Allowances\n\n| Project Stage | Contingency % |\n|---------------|---------------|\n| Feasibility | 15-25% |\n| Outline design | 10-15% |\n| Detailed design | 5-10% |\n| Tender | 2-5% |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Always include inflation allowance for projects extending beyond 12 months. Nigerian inflation averages 15-20% annually.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Bill of Quantities Pricing (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## BOQ Pricing Exercise\n\nThis exercise practices **strategic pricing** of a bill of quantities.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Project**: 20-unit residential estate, Enugu\n**Your Role**: Contractor''s QS — pricing the tender BOQ\n**Budget**: ₦1.2 billion\n\n### Exercise Tasks\n\n**Task 1: Rate Build-Up**\nBuild up rates for these items:\n1. Excavation for foundations\n2. RC foundation concrete 1:2:4\n3. 9-inch blockwork in cement mortar 1:6\n4. Internal plastering 15mm thick\n5. Ceramic floor tiling\n\n**Task 2: Strategic Pricing**\nFor each item, decide:\n- Mark up or mark down?\n- Risk items to increase?\n- Opportunities to optimise?\n\n**Task 3: Preliminaries Pricing**\nPrice the preliminaries section considering:\n- Site establishment costs\n- Scaffolding requirements\n- Temporary services\n- Health and safety\n\n### Pricing Strategy Tips\n\n1. **Front-load** high-risk items\n2. **Reduce** rates on items you can execute efficiently\n3. **Increase** provisional sums and daywork rates\n4. **Include** adequate overhead recovery\n\n### Self-Assessment\n\n- [ ] Are rates competitive but profitable?\n- [ ] Have you included adequate contingencies?\n- [ ] Are preliminaries realistic?\n- [ ] Have you considered cash flow implications?\n- [ ] Did you check the arithmetic?' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 1: Valuation & Interim Certificates
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Valuation & Interim Certificates\n\nValuation is the process of **assessing the value of work done** for payment purposes.\n\n---\n\n### Interim Valuation Process\n\n1. Contractor submits measurement of work done\n2. QS verifies quantities on site\n3. Apply contract rates to verified quantities\n4. Add materials on site\n5. Deduct retention (typically 5%)\n6. Issue interim certificate\n\n### Valuation Principles\n\n- Value work actually done, not work programmed\n- Use contract rates where applicable\n- Daywork for unmeasured work\n- Materials on site at cost (not installed rates)\n\n### Retention\n\n| Stage | Retention Held | Maximum |\n|-------|---------------|---------|\n| Interim | 5% | 5% of contract sum |\n| Practical completion | Half released | 2.5% |\n| Defects liability | Balance released | 0% |\n\n### Certificate Contents\n\n- Value of work done\n- Less previous certificates\n- Less retention\n- Net amount due\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Always inspect work before certifying payment. A certificate is a professional opinion — ensure accuracy.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: Final Account Preparation
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Final Account Preparation\n\nThe final account is the **financial settlement** of a construction contract.\n\n---\n\n### Final Account Structure\n\n1. **Original contract sum**\n2. **Variations** (additions and omissions)\n3. **Dayworks**\n4. **Provisional sums** (actual cost)\n5. **Claims** (loss and expense)\n6. **Deductions** (defects, liquidated damages)\n7. **Net sum due**\n\n### Common Issues\n\n| Issue | Cause | Solution |\n|-------|-------|----------|\n| Unagreed variations | Poor documentation | Establish variation log |\n| Excessive claims | Weak programme records | Maintain programme updates |\n| Rate disputes | Vague specifications | Agree rates during works |\n| Retention disputes | Defects not rectified | Regular inspections |\n\n### Timeline\n\n| Stage | Duration |\n|-------|----------|\n| Contractor submission | 3 months |\n| QS review | 1-2 months |\n| Negotiation | 1-3 months |\n| Agreement | 1 month |\n| **Total** | **6-9 months** |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Start final account discussions during the project, not after completion.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Commercial Management Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Commercial Management Case Study\n\n### Project: Shopping Mall, Abuja — ₦5.2 billion\n\n---\n\n### Background\n\n| Parameter | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Client | Private developer |\n| Contract form | JCT SBC 2016 |\n| Duration | 18 months |\n| Contractor | Julius Berger Nigeria |\n\n### Commercial Challenges\n\n1. **Payment delays** — Client facing financing issues\n2. **Scope changes** — Anchor tenant requirements changed\n3. **Material escalation** — Steel prices increased 25%\n4. **Foreign exchange** — Imported items affected by FX volatility\n\n### How You Would Manage\n\n**Payment Management**:\n- Issue payment reminders promptly\n- Apply contractual interest provisions\n- Negotiate payment plan with client\n\n**Variation Management**:\n- Issue instruction before work proceeds\n- Price variations promptly\n- Track variation budget separately\n\n**Claims Management**:\n- Prepare contemporaneous records\n- Give notice within 28 days\n- Quantify impact on programme and cost\n\n### Key Outcomes\n\n- Project completed 3 months late (extensions granted)\n- Final account agreed at ₦5.8 billion (11.5% above contract sum)\n- Contractor achieved 7% net profit margin\n- Client received a quality building within revised budget' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Risk Management & Allocation
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Risk Management & Allocation\n\nEffective risk management protects **profit margins** and project outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Risk Categories\n\n| Category | Examples |\n|----------|----------|\n| Financial | FX fluctuation, inflation, cash flow |\n| Technical | Design errors, soil conditions |\n| Commercial | Client insolvency, payment delays |\n| Political | Policy changes, regulations |\n| Environmental | Weather, contamination |\n\n### Risk Allocation Principles\n\n| Risk | Typical Allocation |\n|------|-------------------|\n| Ground conditions | Employer (unless contractor investigates) |\n| Design errors | Employer (traditional) / Contractor (D&B) |\n| Weather delays | Shared (with EOT provisions) |\n| Material escalation | Contractor (fixed price) / Employer (cost-plus) |\n| Force majeure | Shared |\n\n### Risk Mitigation Strategies\n\n1. **Avoid** — Eliminate the risk (change design/method)\n2. **Transfer** — Insurance, bonds, subcontracting\n3. **Mitigate** — Reduce likelihood or impact\n4. **Accept** — Contingency allowance\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Document all risk decisions. In disputes, the allocation of risk is often the central issue.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Claims Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Claims Management\n\nClaims management is a **critical skill** for protecting contractor profitability.\n\n---\n\n### Types of Claims\n\n| Claim Type | Entitlement | Time Limit |\n|-----------|-------------|------------|\n| Extension of Time | Delay by employer | 28 days notice |\n| Variation | Change in scope | As instructed |\n| Loss and Expense | Prolongation/disruption | 28 days notice |\n| Acceleration | Forced acceleration | 28 days notice |\n\n### EOT Claim Requirements\n\n1. Notice within 28 days\n2. Evidence of delay event\n3. Causation analysis\n4. Programme impact\n5. Quantum calculation\n\n### Claims Preparation\n\n**Documentation Needed**:\n- Contract documents\n- Programme records\n- Cost records\n- Correspondence\n- Site records\n- Photographic evidence\n\n### Common Pitfalls\n\n1. Late notice — losing entitlement\n2. Poor documentation — insufficient evidence\n3. Weak causation — no link between event and delay\n4. Inflated claims — loss of credibility\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Start claims preparation early. The best claims are built on contemporaneous records.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 4, Module 3: Claims Workshop (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Claims Workshop — Exercise\n\nPrepare a **loss and expense claim** based on the following scenario.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Project**: 100-unit housing estate, Port Harcourt\n**Contract**: JCT SBC 2016\n**Contract Sum**: ₦3.8 billion\n**Original Duration**: 24 months\n**Actual Duration**: 30 months (6 months delay)\n\n### Delay Events\n\n1. **Month 3-5**: Client late in providing access to Phase 2 site\n2. **Month 8-10**: Unforeseen ground conditions (rock)\n3. **Month 12-14**: Client instructed design changes to 30 units\n4. **Month 16-18**: Exceptional rainfall (above 20-year average)\n\n### Your Task\n\n1. **Analyse** which events qualify for EOT\n2. **Prepare** a preliminary EOT claim\n3. **Calculate** prolongation costs using the following data:\n   - Preliminaries: ₦45 million/month\n   - Head office overheads: ₦12 million/month\n   - Finance costs: 2% per month on outstanding amounts\n4. **Prepare** a claims narrative\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Correct identification of qualifying events | 30% |\n| Accurate quantum calculation | 30% |\n| Professional presentation | 20% |\n| Legal understanding | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 5, Module 1: Strategic Commercial Leadership
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Strategic Commercial Leadership\n\nAt the director level, commercial management becomes **strategic and portfolio-focused**.\n\n---\n\n### Strategic Commercial Functions\n\n1. **Portfolio Management** — Overseeing multiple project P&Ls\n2. **Risk Governance** — Enterprise-level risk framework\n3. **Commercial Strategy** — Pricing, tendering, procurement strategy\n4. **Business Development** — Winning work, client retention\n\n### Board-Level Commercial Decisions\n\n- Market entry/expansion\n- Major bid/no-bid decisions\n- Joint ventures and partnerships\n- Financial planning and budgeting\n\n### KPIs for Commercial Performance\n\n| KPI | Target |\n|-----|--------|\n| Gross margin | >15% |\n| Net profit margin | >5% |\n| Cash conversion | >90% |\n| Claims recovery rate | >80% |\n| Tender win rate | >25% |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: At this level, your decisions affect the entire organisation. Data-driven decision-making is essential.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: Multi-Project Financial Control (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Multi-Project Financial Control — Case Study\n\nManaging finances across **5 concurrent projects** as Commercial Director.\n\n---\n\n### Portfolio Overview\n\n| Project | Value (₦) | Status | Margin |\n|---------|----------|--------|--------|\n| Office tower, Lagos | 8.5B | 60% complete | 8.2% |\n| Residential estate, Abuja | 3.2B | 85% complete | 11.5% |\n| Hospital, Enugu | 5.1B | 30% complete | 6.8% |\n| Road project, Kano | 2.8B | 45% complete | 9.1% |\n| Hotel, PH | 4.0B | Tender stage | 10.0% (target) |\n\n### Commercial Dashboard\n\n**Monthly Monitoring**:\n- Revenue recognition vs cost recognition\n- Cash flow by project\n- Variation tracking\n- Claims status\n- Risk register updates\n\n### Key Decisions Required\n\n1. **Resource allocation** — Which project needs senior QS support?\n2. **Cash management** — Which projects are generating cash vs consuming?\n3. **Risk escalation** — Hospital project margin under pressure\n4. **Tender pricing** — Hotel bid margin optimisation\n\n### Lessons Learned\n\n1. Centralised commercial reporting enables portfolio visibility\n2. Early warning systems prevent margin erosion\n3. Regular commercial reviews keep projects on track\n4. Knowledge transfer between projects improves efficiency' WHERE pathway_slug = 'commercial-management' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

-- ─── PATHWAY 3: Construction Project Management ──────────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Project Management Fundamentals
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Project Management Fundamentals\n\nProject management ensures construction projects are delivered **on time, within budget, and to specification**.\n\n---\n\n### The Triple Constraint\n\n```\n        Time\n       /    \\\n      /      \\\n   Cost ──── Quality\n```\n\n### PM Knowledge Areas\n\n1. **Scope Management** — What needs to be delivered\n2. **Time Management** — When it will be delivered\n3. **Cost Management** — How much it will cost\n4. **Quality Management** — Standards to achieve\n5. **Risk Management** — What could go wrong\n6. **Communication Management** — Stakeholder engagement\n7. **Procurement Management** — How to source resources\n\n### Project Lifecycle\n\n```\nInitiation → Planning → Execution → Monitoring → Closing\n```\n\n### Nigerian Construction Context\n\n| Challenge | Impact |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Payment delays | Cash flow problems |\n| Power supply | Productivity reduction |\n| Infrastructure | Access and logistics |\n| Regulation | Approval delays |\n| Skilled labour | Quality and productivity |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Successful project managers combine technical knowledge with strong people skills.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Construction Process Overview
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Construction Process Overview\n\nUnderstanding the **project lifecycle** from concept to handover.\n\n---\n\n### RIBA Plan of Work (Adapted for Nigeria)\n\n| Stage | Description | Duration |\n|-------|-------------|----------|\n| 0 | Strategic definition | 1-2 months |\n| 1 | Preparation and brief | 1-2 months |\n| 2 | Concept design | 2-3 months |\n| 3 | Spatial coordination | 2-3 months |\n| 4 | Technical design | 3-4 months |\n| 5 | Manufacturing and construction | 12-24 months |\n| 6 | Handover | 1 month |\n| 7 | Use | Ongoing |\n\n### Key Milestones\n\n1. **Client brief approved**\n2. **Planning permission granted**\n3. **Tender award**\n4. **Construction commencement**\n5. **Practical completion**\n6. **Final account agreed**\n7. **Defects liability period ends**\n\n### Roles and Responsibilities\n\n| Role | Responsibility |\n|------|---------------|\n| Client | Funding, brief, decisions |\n| Architect | Design, contract administration |\n| QS | Cost management, procurement |\n| Structural Engineer | Structural design |\n| M&E Engineer | Services design |\n| Contractor | Construction delivery |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Understanding the construction process helps you anticipate problems before they occur.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: Planning & Scheduling
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Planning & Scheduling\n\nEffective planning is the **backbone** of project delivery.\n\n---\n\n### Scheduling Methods\n\n| Method | Description | Use Case |\n|--------|-------------|----------|\n| Gantt chart | Bar chart showing activities | Simple projects |\n| Network diagram | Logic-based sequence | Complex projects |\n| Critical path | Longest path determines duration | All projects |\n| PERT | Probabilistic duration estimates | High uncertainty |\n\n### Critical Path Method\n\n1. List all activities\n2. Identify dependencies\n3. Estimate durations\n4. Calculate early/late starts and finishes\n5. Identify the critical path (longest path)\n6. Calculate float on non-critical activities\n\n### Programme Tips\n\n1. Include all activities — don''t miss preliminaries\n2. Show logic links between activities\n3. Include milestones for key dates\n4. Show resources and cash flow\n5. Update regularly — monthly minimum\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The programme is a living document. An outdated programme is worse than no programme.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Resource Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Resource Management\n\nManaging labour, plant, and materials efficiently.\n\n---\n\n### Resource Planning\n\n| Resource | Planning Consideration |\n|----------|----------------------|\n| Labour | Skills, availability, productivity |\n| Plant | Capacity, mobilisation, cost |\n| Materials | Lead times, storage, waste |\n\n### Labour Management\n\n- **Workforce planning** — Right numbers, right skills\n- **Productivity monitoring** — Output per worker per day\n- **Overtime management** — Cost vs benefit analysis\n\n### Plant Management\n\n| Plant Type | Hire vs Buy Decision |\n|-----------|---------------------|\n| Excavator | Hire for <6 months |\n| Tower crane | Hire for project duration |\n| Concrete mixer | Buy if recurring need |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Resource levelling can significantly reduce project costs by avoiding peaks and troughs in demand.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 3: Planning Exercise
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Planning Exercise\n\nCreate a **project schedule** for a residential building.\n\n---\n\n### Project Parameters\n\n- 3-bedroom detached house\n- Floor area: 250 m²\n- RC frame structure\n- Duration target: 12 months\n\n### Tasks\n\n1. List all major activities\n2. Estimate durations for each\n3. Identify dependencies\n4. Draw a simple network diagram\n5. Identify the critical path\n6. Create a Gantt chart\n\n### Expected Activities\n\n- Site clearance and excavation\n- Foundation works\n- Superstructure (columns, beams, slabs)\n- Blockwork\n- Roofing\n- Door and window installation\n- First fix M&E\n- Plastering and finishing\n- Second fix M&E\n- External works\n- Snagging and handover' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 3, Module 1: Contract Forms & Procurement
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Contract Forms & Procurement\n\nChoosing the right **procurement route** is critical for project success.\n\n---\n\n### Procurement Routes\n\n| Route | Description | Best For |\n|-------|-------------|----------|\n| Traditional | Design-bid-build | Clear design, competitive tender |\n| Design & Build | Single point responsibility | Speed, budget certainty |\n| Management | Package deal | Complex, fast-track |\n| PPP/PF2 | Private finance | Public infrastructure |\n\n### Contract Forms in Nigeria\n\n| Form | Origin | Use |\n|------|--------|-----|\n| JCT | UK | Buildings |\n| FIDIC | International | Infrastructure |\n| NEC | UK | Growing adoption |\n| GCC | Nigeria | Government projects |\n\n### Procurement Considerations\n\n1. **Project complexity** — Complex = management route\n2. **Programme** — Fast-track = design & build\n3. **Budget certainty** — Fixed price = traditional\n4. **Design control** — Client control = traditional\n5. **Risk appetite** — Low risk = traditional\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The procurement route determines who carries design risk, programme risk, and cost risk.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: Quality Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Quality Management\n\nQuality management ensures projects meet **specification and standards**.\n\n---\n\n### Quality Management System\n\n1. **Quality Plan** — Project-specific quality procedures\n2. **Inspection and Test Plan (ITP)** — When to inspect\n3. **Non-Conformance Register** — Track defects\n4. **Corrective Actions** — Fix and prevent recurrence\n\n### Inspection Points\n\n| Stage | Inspection |\n|-------|------------|\n| Foundation | Excavation, reinforcement, concrete |\n| Superstructure | Formwork, reinforcement, concrete |\n| Blockwork | Alignment, plumb, mortar quality |\n| Finishes | Surface preparation, application quality |\n\n### Quality Standards (Nigeria)\n\n- **Nigerian Building Code** — Building regulations\n- **NIS standards** — Material standards\n- **BS/EN standards** — International standards adopted\n- **Project specifications** — Contract-specific requirements\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Quality is cheaper than rework. Prevention is always better than cure.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Procurement Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Procurement Case Study\n\nSelect the **optimal procurement route** for a real scenario.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Project**: 200-bed teaching hospital, Ibadan\n**Budget**: ₦45 billion\n**Duration**: 36 months\n**Client**: Oyo State Government\n\n### Analysis\n\n**Factors**:\n1. Complex project — multiple specialist packages\n2. Government procurement rules apply\n3. International funding — FIDIC preferred\n4. Fast-track potential — programme pressure\n\n### Procurement Options\n\n| Option | Pros | Cons |\n|--------|------|------|\n| Traditional (FIDIC Red) | Client design control | Longer programme |\n| Design & Build | Single point responsibility | Less design control |\n| Management Contract | Fast-track, flexibility | Higher risk |\n| PPP | No upfront capital | Complex procurement |\n\n### Recommendation\n\n**Management Contract with FIDIC**:\n- Fast-track delivery\n- Experienced management contractor\n- Specialist packages under management contractor\n- FIDIC conditions for international funding compliance\n\n### Key Learning Points\n\n1. Match procurement to project characteristics\n2. Consider all stakeholders, not just the client\n3. Balance speed, cost, and quality\n4. Ensure compliance with funding requirements' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Risk & Change Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Risk & Change Management\n\nManaging risks and changes protects **project outcomes**.\n\n---\n\n### Risk Management Process\n\n1. **Identify** — What could go wrong?\n2. **Assess** — How likely and how severe?\n3. **Respond** — What will we do about it?\n4. **Monitor** — Track and update\n\n### Change Management\n\n**Types of Change**:\n- Design changes\n- Scope additions/omissions\n- Programme changes\n- Resource changes\n\n**Change Control Process**:\n1. Change request submitted\n2. Impact assessment (time, cost, quality)\n3. Approval/rejection\n4. Implementation\n5. Documentation update\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Uncontrolled change is the #1 cause of project overruns. Implement a formal change control process from day one.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Stakeholder Communication
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Stakeholder Communication\n\nEffective communication is the **glue** that holds projects together.\n\n---\n\n### Stakeholder Analysis\n\n| Stakeholder | Interest | Influence | Strategy |\n|-------------|----------|-----------|----------|\n| Client | High | High | Manage closely |\n| End users | High | Medium | Keep informed |\n| Regulators | Medium | High | Comply fully |\n| Neighbours | Medium | Low | Keep informed |\n| Contractor | High | High | Manage closely |\n\n### Communication Methods\n\n| Method | Use Case | Frequency |\n|--------|----------|-----------|\n| Progress meeting | Regular updates | Weekly |\n| Report | Formal documentation | Monthly |\n| Email | Quick communication | As needed |\n| Site notice | Safety/community | As needed |\n\n### Meeting Management\n\n1. **Agenda** — Circulate in advance\n2. **Minutes** — Record and distribute within 24 hours\n3. **Actions** — Assign responsibility and deadline\n4. **Follow up** — Track completion\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The quality of communication determines the quality of the project. Over-communicate rather than under-communicate.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 4, Module 3: Project Recovery Exercise
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Project Recovery Exercise\n\nRescue a **failing project** scenario.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Project**: Commercial office complex, Lagos\n**Original budget**: ₦6.5 billion (80% complete)\n**Current forecast**: ₦8.2 billion (26% overrun)\n**Programme**: 6 months behind schedule\n\n### Issues\n\n1. **Design changes** — ₦800M in variations\n2. **Material escalation** — ₦500M additional cost\n3. **Productivity loss** — Poor labour management\n4. **Quality defects** — Rework required ₦200M\n5. **Payment delays** — Contractor cash flow problems\n\n### Your Task\n\nAs the newly appointed project recovery manager:\n1. **Diagnose** the root causes\n2. **Develop** a recovery plan\n3. **Prioritise** actions (quick wins vs strategic)\n4. **Prepare** a stakeholder communication plan\n5. **Present** your recovery strategy\n\n### Recovery Strategies\n\n| Strategy | Impact | Timeline |\n|----------|--------|----------|\n| Value engineering | Cost reduction | 1-2 months |\n| Programme compression | Time recovery | Immediate |\n| Resource reallocation | Productivity improvement | 2-4 weeks |\n| Claims management | Cost recovery | 3-6 months |\n| Design freeze | Stop scope creep | Immediate |\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Root cause analysis | 25% |\n| Recovery plan quality | 30% |\n| Stakeholder management | 20% |\n| Presentation | 25% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 5, Module 1: Programme Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Programme Management\n\nManaging **multiple projects** as a coordinated programme.\n\n---\n\n### Programme vs Project\n\n| Aspect | Project | Programme |\n|--------|---------|----------|\n| Scope | Single deliverable | Multiple related projects |\n| Duration | Finite | Ongoing |\n| Focus | Deliverables | Benefits |\n| Management | Project manager | Programme manager |\n\n### Programme Governance\n\n1. **Programme board** — Strategic oversight\n2. **Programme manager** — Day-to-day coordination\n3. **Project managers** — Individual project delivery\n4. **PMO** — Standards, reporting, support\n\n### Benefits Management\n\n- Identify expected benefits\n- Measure benefits realisation\n- Adjust programme to maximise benefits\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Programme management is about achieving outcomes, not just delivering projects.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: Strategic Project Leadership (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Strategic Project Leadership — Case Study\n\nLeading a **₦200 billion infrastructure programme** in Nigeria.\n\n---\n\n### Programme Overview\n\n**Nigerian Infrastructure Development Programme (NIDP)**\n- **Scope**: Roads, bridges, public buildings across 6 states\n- **Duration**: 5 years\n- **Budget**: ₦200 billion\n- **Funding**: Federal government + World Bank\n\n### Leadership Challenges\n\n1. **Multi-stakeholder coordination** — Federal, state, local, international\n2. **Political environment** — Election cycles, policy changes\n3. **Capacity building** — Developing local teams\n4. **Quality assurance** — Consistent standards across states\n5. **Financial management** — Multiple funding sources\n\n### Your Role: Programme Director\n\n**Key Responsibilities**:\n- Strategic direction and oversight\n- Stakeholder management at highest levels\n- Risk governance\n- Team development\n- Benefits realisation\n\n### Leadership Framework\n\n1. **Vision** — Clear programme objectives\n2. **People** — Right team, right skills\n3. **Process** — Standardised delivery approach\n4. **Performance** — KPI-driven management\n5. **Communication** — Transparent reporting\n\n> **Pro Tip**: At the programme level, leadership is about creating the environment for success, not managing every detail.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'project-management' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

-- ─── PATHWAY 4: Real Estate & Property Advisory ──────────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Property Market Overview
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Property Market Overview\n\nUnderstanding the **Nigerian real estate market** is essential for property advisory.\n\n---\n\n### Nigerian Property Market Segments\n\n| Segment | Key Markets | Typical Yields |\n|---------|------------|----------------|\n| Residential | Lagos, Abuja, PH | 5-10% |\n| Commercial office | Lagos (VI, Lekki), Abuja | 8-15% |\n| Retail | Major cities | 10-18% |\n| Industrial | Lagos, Ogun | 12-20% |\n| Hospitality | Lagos, Abuja | 15-25% |\n\n### Market Drivers\n\n1. **Population growth** — 2.5% annually\n2. **Urbanisation** — Rural-to-urban migration\n3. **Economic growth** — GDP and income levels\n4. **Infrastructure** — Roads, power, water\n5. **Regulation** — Planning, taxation\n\n### Property Valuation Concepts\n\n- **Market value** — Price in open market\n- **Investment value** — Value to specific investor\n- **Insurance value** — Cost to rebuild\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Location is the #1 driver of property value in Nigeria. Understand micro-markets within cities.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Property Valuation Basics
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Property Valuation Basics\n\nProperty valuation determines the **monetary worth** of real estate.\n\n---\n\n### Valuation Methods\n\n| Method | Application | Key Factors |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|\n| Comparison | Market transactions | Recent sales data |\n| Investment | Rental properties | Yield, income |\n| Cost | New buildings | Replacement cost |\n| Residual | Development projects | Profit margin |\n\n### Comparison Method Example\n\n- Comparable sale: ₦50M for 300m² house\n- Subject property: 350m² house\n- Location adjustment: +5%\n- Condition adjustment: -10%\n- **Valuation = ₦50M × (350/300) × 1.05 × 0.90 = ₦55.1M**\n\n### Investment Method Example\n\n- Annual rent: ₦2,000,000\n- Yield: 10%\n- **Capital Value = ₦2M / 0.10 = ₦20,000,000**\n\n### Key Principles\n\n1. **Market value** — Not forced sale value\n2. **Highest and best use** — Optimal use of property\n3. **Caveat emptor** — Buyer beware\n4. **Duplicating provision** — Consider alternative supply\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Always inspect the property personally. Desktop valuations miss site-specific issues.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: Investment Analysis
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Investment Analysis\n\nProperty investment analysis measures **financial viability**.\n\n---\n\n### Key Metrics\n\n| Metric | Formula | Target |\n|--------|---------|--------|\n| Net yield | (Annual rent - expenses) / Purchase price × 100 | >8% |\n| Return on investment | Annual return / Total investment × 100 | >15% |\n| Payback period | Total investment / Annual return | <10 years |\n\n### DCF Analysis\n\n**Discounted Cash Flow** measures the present value of future income.\n\n**Example**:\n- Year 1 rent: ₦5M\n- Annual growth: 5%\n- Discount rate: 12%\n- Period: 10 years\n- **NPV = ₦28.5M**\n\n### Nigerian Property Yields (2024)\n\n| Location | Residential | Commercial | Industrial |\n|----------|------------|-----------|------------|\n| Lagos (Prime) | 4-6% | 8-12% | 12-18% |\n| Abuja (Prime) | 5-7% | 9-13% | 10-15% |\n| Port Harcourt | 6-8% | 10-15% | 12-16% |\n| Other cities | 8-12% | 12-18% | 15-22% |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Yields in Nigeria are higher than many international markets, reflecting higher risk levels.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Development Appraisal (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Development Appraisal Exercise\n\nPrepare a **financial viability assessment** for a development project.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Site**: 2,000m² plot in Lekki, Lagos\n**Proposed**: 12 luxury apartments\n**Total GIA**: 1,800m² (150m² per unit)\n\n### Exercise Tasks\n\n1. **Estimate development cost**\n2. **Calculate revenue potential**\n3. **Assess financial viability**\n4. **Determine site value**\n\n### Data Provided\n\n| Cost Element | Rate (₦/m²) |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Construction | 350,000 |\n| Professional fees | 35,000 |\n| Infrastructure | 25,000 |\n| Contingency | 15,000 |\n\n| Revenue Element | Value (₦) |\n|----------------|----------|\n| Sale price per unit | 65,000,000 |\n| Parking allocation | 5,000,000 |\n\n### Expected Output\n\n- Development cost: ₦792,000,000\n- Revenue: ₦840,000,000\n- Profit: ₦48,000,000\n- Profit margin: 5.7%\n- **Site value**: Residual method\n\n### Self-Assessment\n\n- [ ] Did you include all cost elements?\n- [ ] Is the revenue estimate realistic?\n- [ ] Did you apply the residual method correctly?\n- [ ] Did you consider timing and cash flow?\n- [ ] Is the profit margin acceptable?' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 1: Estate Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Estate Management\n\nManaging residential and commercial estates effectively.\n\n---\n\n### Estate Management Functions\n\n1. **Financial management** — Service charges, budgets\n2. **Maintenance** — Planned and reactive\n3. **Tenant management** — Leases, disputes\n4. **Compliance** — Safety, regulatory\n5. **Asset management** — Long-term value preservation\n\n### Service Charge Budget\n\n| Category | Typical % |\n|----------|----------|\n| Cleaning and security | 25% |\n| Maintenance and repairs | 30% |\n| Insurance | 10% |\n| Management fees | 15% |\n| Utilities (common areas) | 15% |\n| Reserve fund | 5% |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Transparent financial management builds trust with leaseholders and prevents disputes.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: Facilities Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Facilities Management\n\nBuilding maintenance and operational management.\n\n---\n\n### FM Functions\n\n| Function | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| Hard FM | Building fabric, M&E systems |\n| Soft FM | Cleaning, security, catering |\n| Space management | Optimising building use |\n| Sustainability | Energy, waste, environmental |\n\n### Planned Maintenance\n\n**Lifecycle Costing**:\n- Roof: 25-30 years\n- M&E systems: 15-20 years\n- Decoration: 5-7 years\n- Lifts: 20-25 years\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Planned maintenance is always cheaper than emergency repairs. Budget for lifecycle replacements.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Property Advisory Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Property Advisory Case Study\n\n### Client Brief\n\n**Client**: First Bank of Nigeria\n**Requirement**: New regional headquarters, 5,000m², Abuja\n**Budget**: ₦5 billion (including fit-out)\n**Timeline**: Occupy within 24 months\n\n### Advisory Approach\n\n1. **Needs analysis** — Space requirements, location preferences\n2. **Market search** — Available options (build-to-suit vs lease)\n3. **Financial analysis** — Buy vs lease comparison\n4. **Recommendation** — Best value option\n5. **Implementation** — Procurement and project management\n\n### Key Deliverables\n\n- Property market analysis report\n- Financial comparison (buy vs lease)\n- Recommended option with rationale\n- Implementation plan\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Property advisory is about understanding the client''s business needs, not just property market data.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Portfolio Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Portfolio Management\n\nManaging a **diversified property portfolio** for optimal returns.\n\n---\n\n### Portfolio Strategy\n\n1. **Diversification** — Spread risk across sectors and locations\n2. **Active management** — Regular performance review\n3. **Rebalancing** — Buy/sell to maintain target allocation\n4. **Risk management** — Monitor and mitigate portfolio risks\n\n### Performance Metrics\n\n| Metric | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| Total return | Income + capital growth |\n| Risk-adjusted return | Return relative to risk |\n| Occupancy rate | % of space let |\n| Void period | Average time to re-let |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Portfolio management is about the bigger picture. Individual property decisions should serve the overall portfolio strategy.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Market Research & Analysis (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Market Research & Analysis Exercise\n\nConduct **property market research** for a specific sector.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Task**: Research the Lagos office market for a client considering development\n\n### Research Framework\n\n1. **Supply analysis** — Existing and pipeline stock\n2. **Demand analysis** — Tenant requirements and trends\n3. **Rental analysis** — Current levels and trends\n4. **Yield analysis** — Investment returns\n5. **Forecast** — Market outlook\n\n### Data Sources\n\n- Knight Frank Nigeria reports\n- Broll Nigeria market research\n- Nigerian Bureau of Statistics\n- Estate surveys and valuers\n- Online property portals\n\n### Deliverable\n\nA 10-page market research report with:\n- Executive summary\n- Market overview\n- Supply and demand analysis\n- Recommendations\n- Appendices with data\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Data quality and relevance | 30% |\n| Analysis depth | 30% |\n| Presentation quality | 20% |\n| Recommendations | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 5, Module 1: Property Finance & Investment
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Property Finance & Investment\n\nAdvanced property finance structures for **major developments**.\n\n---\n\n### Finance Structures\n\n| Structure | Description | Use Case |\n|-----------|-------------|----------|\n| Senior debt | Bank loan (60-70% LTV) | Standard development |\n| Mezzanine | Second charge (15-20%) | Bridge funding |\n| Equity | Investor capital | High-return projects |\n| JV | Joint venture | Large schemes |\n\n### Nigerian Property Finance\n\n**Bank Lending**:\n- Maximum LTV: 60-70%\n- Interest rates: 15-25%\n- Tenor: 5-10 years\n\n**REITs in Nigeria**:\n- FTN Nigerian Properties\n- Union Homes REIT\n- ARM Harith Infrastructure\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Understanding finance structures is essential for advising clients on development viability.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: Large-Scale Development Advisory (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Large-Scale Development Advisory — Case Study\n\nAdvising on a **₦50 billion mixed-use development**.\n\n---\n\n### Project: Eko Atlantic City, Lagos (Similar Scale)\n\n**Scope**: Mixed-use waterfront development\n**Phases**: 5 phases over 10 years\n**Components**: Residential, commercial, retail, marina\n\n### Advisory Scope\n\n1. **Development strategy** — Phasing, product mix\n2. **Financial modelling** — Revenue, cost, profit\n3. **Risk assessment** — Political, market, construction\n4. **Procurement strategy** — Packages, contracts\n5. **Marketing strategy** — Pricing, positioning\n\n### Key Issues\n\n1. **Infrastructure** — Roads, power, water, drainage\n2. **Title and consent** — Land ownership verification\n3. **Environmental** — Coastal protection, sustainability\n4. **Market timing** — Supply-demand balance\n\n### Deliverables\n\n- Development strategy report\n- Financial model (10-year DCF)\n- Risk register and mitigation plan\n- Procurement strategy document\n- Implementation roadmap' WHERE pathway_slug = 'real-estate-advisory' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

-- ─── PATHWAY 5: Construction Dispute Resolution ─────────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Dispute Resolution Overview
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Dispute Resolution Overview\n\nDisputes are **common** in construction. Understanding resolution methods is essential.\n\n---\n\n### Types of Construction Disputes\n\n| Type | Common Cause |\n|------|-------------|\n| Payment disputes | Delayed/non-payment |\n| Variation disputes | Scope, pricing disagreements |\n| Delay claims | Programme extensions |\n| Quality disputes | Defective work |\n| Contract interpretation | Ambiguous terms |\n\n### Resolution Methods\n\n| Method | Binding? | Duration | Cost |\n|--------|----------|----------|------|\n| Negotiation | No | Days | Low |\n| Mediation | No | Weeks | Low-Medium |\n| Adjudication | Yes (temp) | 28 days | Medium |\n| Arbitration | Yes | 6-18 months | Medium-High |\n| Litigation | Yes | 2-5 years | High |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Always attempt negotiation first. Most disputes can be resolved without formal proceedings.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Nigerian Construction Law Basics
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Nigerian Construction Law Basics\n\nKey legal principles for construction professionals.\n\n---\n\n### Contract Formation\n\nEssential elements:\n1. **Offer** — Clear proposal\n2. **Acceptance** — Unqualified acceptance\n3. **Consideration** — Price exchanged\n4. **Intention** — Legal intent\n5. **Capacity** — Legal ability to contract\n\n### Breach of Contract\n\n| Type | Description | Remedy |\n|------|-------------|--------|\n| Minor | Partial non-performance | Damages |\n| Material | Substantial non-performance | Termination |\n| Fundamental | Goes to root of contract | Termination + damages |\n\n### Limitation Periods\n\n| Claim Type | Period |\n|------------|--------|\n| Simple contract | 6 years |\n| Deed | 12 years |\n| Negligence | 6 years |\n\n### Key Legislation\n\n- Arbitration and Conciliation Act\n- Nigerian Law of Contract\n- Land Use Act\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Always maintain comprehensive records. In disputes, documentation is your strongest defense.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: Claims Prevention & Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Claims Prevention & Management\n\nPreventing claims is better than managing them.\n\n---\n\n### Prevention Strategies\n\n1. **Clear contracts** — Ambiguity-free documentation\n2. **Good communication** — Regular, documented exchanges\n3. **Fair administration** — Impartial contract management\n4. **Prompt payment** — Avoid cash flow issues\n5. **Quality work** — Minimise defects and rework\n\n### Claims Management\n\n**When a claim arises**:\n1. Acknowledge receipt promptly\n2. Review contract provisions\n3. Assess entitlement and quantum\n4. Engage in without-prejudice discussions\n5. Document all negotiations\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The best claims management strategy is claims prevention through good project management.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Dispute Avoidance Strategies
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Dispute Avoidance Strategies\n\nProactive approaches to **minimise disputes**.\n\n---\n\n### Early Warning Systems\n\n- Regular project meetings\n- Open communication channels\n- Issue escalation procedures\n- Risk register reviews\n\n### Partnering and Collaboration\n\n- Joint risk identification\n- Shared goals and targets\n- Dispute resolution boards\n- Pain/gain share mechanisms\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Partnering doesn''t eliminate disputes, but it creates an environment where disputes are resolved faster and cheaper.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 3: Claims Workshop (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Claims Workshop — Exercise\n\nPrepare a **claim submission** based on a construction scenario.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Project**: Government hospital, Ogun State\n**Contract**: FIDIC Red Book\n**Claim**: Extension of time and loss and expense\n\n### Delay Events\n\n1. Late access to site (3 months)\n2. Unforeseen ground conditions (2 months)\n3. Client-directed design changes (4 months)\n\n### Your Task\n\n1. Review the contract provisions\n2. Identify qualifying events\n3. Prepare a claims notice\n4. Draft a claims submission\n5. Calculate prolongation costs\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Legal analysis | 30% |\n| Quantum accuracy | 30% |\n| Presentation quality | 20% |\n| Professional conduct | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 3, Module 1: Adjudication Process
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Adjudication Process\n\nStatutory adjudication provides **rapid dispute resolution**.\n\n---\n\n### What is Adjudication?\n\nA binding (but temporary) decision by an independent adjudicator, typically within 28 days.\n\n### Process\n\n1. **Notice of adjudication**\n2. **Appointment of adjudicator**\n3. **Referral** (adjudicator''s claim)\n4. **Response**\n5. **Reply** (if permitted)\n6. **Decision** within 28 days\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Payment disputes\n- Quick decisions needed\n- Interim relief required\n\n### Enforcement\n\n- Decision is binding unless referred to arbitration/court\n- Enforceable as a court judgment\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Adjudication is fast and cost-effective for payment disputes. Use it strategically.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: Mediation Techniques
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Mediation Techniques\n\nCommercial mediation for **construction disputes**.\n\n---\n\n### What is Mediation?\n\nA voluntary, confidential process where a neutral mediator helps parties reach a settlement.\n\n### Mediation Process\n\n1. **Agreement to mediate**\n2. **Selection of mediator**\n3. **Joint session** — Opening statements\n4. **Private sessions** — Caucuses between mediator and each party\n5. **Negotiation** — Facilitated discussions\n6. **Settlement** (if reached)\n\n### Mediator Skills\n\n- Active listening\n- Reality testing\n- Reframing\n- Option generation\n- Pressure management\n\n### Benefits\n\n- Preserves relationships\n- Cost-effective (₦100,000-500,000)\n- Confidential\n- Party-controlled outcome\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Mediation succeeds in 60-80% of cases. Always consider it before more formal proceedings.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Mediation Role Play (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Mediation Role Play — Exercise\n\nSimulate a **mediation session** for a construction payment dispute.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Parties**:\n- **Claimant**: ABC Contractors (subcontractor)\n- **Respondent**: XYZ Developers (main contractor)\n\n**Dispute**: Unpaid interim payment of ₦45 million\n\n### Roles\n\n1. **Mediator** — Facilitate resolution\n2. **Claimant representative** — Present claim\n3. **Respondent representative** — Present defence\n\n### Key Issues\n\n1. Quality of work disputed\n2. Programme delays attributed to claimant\n3. Retention held beyond contract period\n4. Relationship damage from payment delays\n\n### Expected Outcome\n\nA mediated settlement addressing:\n- Payment schedule\n- Quality remediation plan\n- Future project relationship\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Mediation technique | 30% |\n| Party representation | 30% |\n| Settlement quality | 25% |\n| Professional conduct | 15% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Arbitration Proceedings
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Arbitration Proceedings\n\nConstruction arbitration under **CIARB and ICC rules**.\n\n---\n\n### Arbitration Process\n\n1. **Request for arbitration**\n2. **Appointment of arbitrator(s)**\n3. **Preliminary meeting**\n4. **Written submissions**\n5. **Hearing**\n6. **Award**\n\n### Costs\n\n| Item | Typical Cost (₦) |\n|------|------------------|\n| Arbitrator fees | 500,000-2,000,000 |\n| Legal representation | 1,000,000-5,000,000 |\n| Expert witnesses | 200,000-1,000,000 |\n| **Total** | **2,000,000-8,000,000** |\n\n### Enforcement\n\n- Enforceable as court judgment\n- Apply to High Court\n- New York Convention for international awards\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Arbitration is preferred in Nigerian construction because it is faster than litigation and provides confidentiality.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Expert Witness Duties
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Expert Witness Duties\n\nRole and responsibilities of **expert witnesses** in construction disputes.\n\n---\n\n### Expert''s Duty\n\n- Duty is to the **tribunal**, not the instructing party\n- Must be impartial and objective\n- Must not act as advocate\n\n### Expert Report Requirements\n\n1. Statement of truth\n2. Terms of reference\n3. Assumptions and qualifications\n4. Detailed analysis\n5. Conclusions and recommendations\n\n### Common Expert Disciplines\n\n| Discipline | Typical Role |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| Quantum expert | Cost/damages assessment |\n| Delay expert | Programme analysis |\n| Technical expert | Defects and standards |\n| Valuation expert | Property assessment |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The credibility of an expert witness depends on objectivity. Never overstate your case.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 4, Module 3: Arbitration Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Arbitration Case Study\n\nHandle a **complex arbitration** scenario.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Project**: Power station, Niger Delta\n**Claim value**: ₦12 billion\n**Arbitration rules**: ICC\n**Tribunal**: Three arbitrators\n\n### Issues\n\n1. Design liability dispute\n2. Delay and disruption claims\n3. Variation pricing disagreements\n4. Force majeure invocation\n\n### Your Task\n\n1. Prepare written submissions for the quantum expert\n2. Review and critique the opposing expert''s report\n3. Prepare for cross-examination\n4. Draft an opening statement\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Legal analysis | 25% |\n| Quantum assessment | 30% |\n| Presentation quality | 25% |\n| Cross-examination prep | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 5, Module 1: International Dispute Resolution
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## International Dispute Resolution\n\nFIDIC dispute boards and **international arbitration**.\n\n---\n\n### FIDIC Dispute Board\n\n- Standing or ad hoc\n- Provides ongoing dispute avoidance\n- Issues recommendations or decisions\n- Binding unless referred to arbitration\n\n### ICC Arbitration\n\n- International Chamber of Commerce\n- Administered arbitration\n- Global enforcement under New York Convention\n- Costs: $50,000-$500,000+\n\n### LCIA Arbitration\n\n- London Court of International Arbitration\n- Similar to ICC but different procedural rules\n- Common in finance-related construction disputes\n\n> **Pro Tip**: International arbitration is the preferred method for cross-border construction disputes. Understanding the New York Convention is essential.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: High-Value Dispute Strategy (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## High-Value Dispute Strategy — Case Study\n\n### ₦25 Billion Railway Project Dispute\n\n---\n\n### Background\n\n**Project**: Lagos-Kano railway rehabilitation\n**Contractor**: Chinese construction firm\n**Client**: Federal Government of Nigeria\n**Contract**: FIDIC Silver Book (EPC/Turnkey)\n\n### Claim Elements\n\n| Element | Value (₦B) |\n|---------|-----------|\n| Additional works | 8.5 |\n| Delay costs | 6.2 |\n| Acceleration | 3.8 |\n| Escalation | 4.5 |\n| Finance charges | 2.0 |\n| **Total** | **25.0** |\n\n### Strategic Considerations\n\n1. **Jurisdiction** — Nigerian courts vs international arbitration\n2. **Enforcement** — New York Convention member\n3. **Political sensitivity** — Government project\n4. **Expert selection** — International quantum experts\n5. **Timeline** — 18-24 months\n\n### Your Strategy\n\nAs lead dispute advisor:\n1. Assemble expert team (quantum, delay, technical)\n2. Develop claims narrative\n3. Prepare detailed quantum analysis\n4. Manage arbitration process\n5. Negotiate settlement\n\n### Key Lessons\n\n1. High-value disputes require meticulous preparation\n2. Expert selection is critical\n3. Settlement is often preferable to award\n4. Political considerations affect strategy\n5. Timeline management prevents fatigue' WHERE pathway_slug = 'dispute-resolution' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

-- ─── PATHWAY 6: QS Technology & Digital Construction ────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Digital QS Tools Overview
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Digital QS Tools Overview\n\nModern QS professionals must master **digital tools** for efficiency.\n\n---\n\n### Software Landscape\n\n| Category | Tools | Use Case |\n|----------|-------|----------|\n| Measurement | CostX, PlanSwift, Bluebeam | Quantity takeoff |\n| Cost planning | Sigma, CostX | Cost management |\n| BIM | Revit, ArchiCAD | 3D modelling |\n| Spreadsheets | Excel, Google Sheets | Data analysis |\n| Project MS | Primavera, MS Project | Scheduling |\n\n### Why Digital Matters\n\n1. **Speed** — 30-50% faster measurement\n2. **Accuracy** — Reduced errors\n3. **Collaboration** — Remote work capability\n4. **Changes** — Quick re-measurement\n5. **Professionalism** — Modern practice image\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Start with one tool and master it before adding others. Excel proficiency is the foundation.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Spreadsheet Mastery for QS
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Spreadsheet Mastery for QS\n\nAdvanced Excel/Google Sheets for **quantity surveying**.\n\n---\n\n### Essential Functions\n\n| Function | QS Application |\n|----------|----------------|\n| VLOOKUP/XLOOKUP | Rate lookup |\n| SUMIF/COUNTIF | Quantity aggregation |\n| Pivot Tables | Data analysis |\n| Conditional formatting | Data validation |\n| Charts | Cost visualisation |\n\n### BOQ Template\n\nCreate a standard BOQ template with:\n- Automatic quantity calculation\n- Rate lookup from database\n- Automatic total calculation\n- Variance tracking\n\n### Tips for QS Spreadsheets\n\n1. Use named ranges for clarity\n2. Protect formula cells\n3. Version control — date-stamp files\n4. Backup regularly\n5. Use data validation for consistency\n\n> **Pro Tip**: A well-built spreadsheet can save hours of manual calculation. Invest time in templates.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: BIM for Quantity Surveyors
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## BIM for Quantity Surveyors\n\nBuilding Information Modelling is **transforming** construction.\n\n---\n\n### BIM Dimensions\n\n| Dimension | Description |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| 3D | Spatial representation |\n| 4D | Time/scheduling |\n| 5D | Cost/quantity |\n| 6D | Sustainability |\n| 7D | Facility management |\n\n### BIM for QS\n\n**Benefits**:\n- Accurate quantity extraction\n- Reduced measurement errors\n- Faster BOQ preparation\n- Better cost control\n- Clash detection\n\n### LOD Levels\n\n| LOD | Description | QS Use |\n|-----|-------------|--------|\n| 100 | Conceptual | Approximate estimates |\n| 200 | Approximate | Budget estimates |\n| 300 | Precise | Detailed measurement |\n| 400 | Construction | As-built measurement |\n\n### Getting Started\n\n1. Learn CostX or similar takeoff software\n2. Understand Revit basics\n3. Practice with sample models\n4. Apply to small projects first\n\n> **Pro Tip**: BIM adoption is growing in Nigeria. Early adopters will have a significant competitive advantage.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Digital Measurement Tools
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Digital Measurement Tools\n\nComparing available **measurement software**.\n\n---\n\n### Tool Comparison\n\n| Software | Platform | Key Features | Price |\n|----------|----------|--------------|-------|\n| CostX | Windows | BIM integration, 2D/3D | High |\n| PlanSwift | Windows | Easy to use, templates | Medium |\n| Bluebeam | Windows/Mac | PDF markup, collaboration | Medium |\n| Cubit | Windows | Flexibility, templates | Medium |\n\n### Digital vs Traditional\n\n| Aspect | Traditional | Digital |\n|--------|-------------|----------|\n| Speed | Slow | Fast |\n| Accuracy | Variable | High |\n| Changes | Time-consuming | Quick |\n| Storage | Physical | Digital |\n\n### Implementation Tips\n\n1. Start small — one project at a time\n2. Train staff — invest in training\n3. Maintain traditional skills\n4. Backup data regularly\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Start with a free trial of PlanSwift or Bluebeam before committing to expensive software.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 3: BIM Exercise
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## BIM Exercise\n\nExtract quantities from a **BIM model**.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\nUsing a sample Revit model of a 3-storey office building:\n\n1. Import the model into CostX (or similar)\n2. Extract quantities for:\n   - Concrete (foundations, columns, beams, slabs)\n   - Blockwork (walls by type)\n   - Finishes (floors, walls, ceilings)\n3. Compare with manual measurement\n4. Analyse accuracy differences\n\n### Expected Learning Outcomes\n\n- Understand BIM model navigation\n- Extract quantities from 3D models\n- Compare digital vs traditional measurement\n- Identify when BIM provides value\n\n### Self-Assessment\n\n- [ ] Can you navigate a BIM model?\n- [ ] Can you extract quantities by element?\n- [ ] Can you map quantities to BOQ items?\n- [ ] Do you understand LOD implications?\n- [ ] Can you identify BIM errors?' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 3, Module 1: Cloud-Based Cost Management
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Cloud-Based Cost Management\n\nCollaborative platforms for **modern cost management**.\n\n---\n\n### Cloud Benefits\n\n1. **Accessibility** — Work from anywhere\n2. **Collaboration** — Real-time team work\n3. **Storage** — Unlimited digital storage\n4. **Security** — Professional data protection\n\n### QSToolkit Cloud Features\n\n- Web-based cost management\n- AI-powered rate suggestions\n- BOQ preparation tools\n- Multi-device access\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Cloud tools enable remote work and collaboration, essential for modern QS practice.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: AI in Quantity Surveying
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## AI in Quantity Surveying\n\nHow AI is **transforming** cost estimation.\n\n---\n\n### Current AI Applications\n\n| Application | Technology | Benefit |\n|-------------|-----------|----------|\n| Rate Suggestion | Machine Learning | Faster pricing |\n| BOQ Generation | NLP + ML | Automated measurement |\n| Cost Prediction | Regression AI | Accurate estimates |\n| Risk Assessment | Classification AI | Better risk management |\n\n### QSToolkit AI Features\n\n1. **Rate Suggestions** — AI-powered rate recommendations\n2. **Cost Estimation** — Preliminary cost estimates\n3. **Risk Analysis** — Project risk assessment\n4. **Market Intelligence** — Price trend analysis\n\n### AI Adoption Roadmap\n\n1. **Phase 1**: Awareness — Understand AI capabilities\n2. **Phase 2**: Integration — Adopt AI tools\n3. **Phase 3**: Optimisation — Customise AI models\n\n> **Pro Tip**: AI supports, not replaces, professional judgment. Use AI as a tool to enhance your expertise.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Tech Integration Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Tech Integration Case Study\n\nImplementing **digital tools** on a live construction project.\n\n---\n\n### Project: 50-Unit Residential Estate, Lagos\n\n**Objective**: Digitise all QS processes\n\n### Implementation Plan\n\n| Phase | Tool | Duration | Cost (₦) |\n|-------|------|----------|----------|\n| 1 | CostX (measurement) | 2 months | 500,000 |\n| 2 | Cloud BOQ platform | 1 month | 200,000 |\n| 3 | BIM integration | 3 months | 800,000 |\n| 4 | AI rate suggestion | Ongoing | 150,000/month |\n\n### Results\n\n| Metric | Before | After | Improvement |\n|--------|--------|-------|-------------|\n| Measurement time | 5 days | 2 days | 60% faster |\n| BOQ preparation | 3 days | 1 day | 67% faster |\n| Error rate | 8% | 2% | 75% reduction |\n| Client satisfaction | Good | Excellent | — |\n\n### Key Lessons\n\n1. **Start small** — Prove value before scaling\n2. **Train the team** — Investment in training pays off\n3. **Maintain quality** — Don''t sacrifice accuracy for speed\n4. **Measure results** — Track improvements' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Data Analytics for QS
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Data Analytics for QS\n\nUsing data to **drive cost decisions**.\n\n---\n\n### Types of Analytics\n\n| Type | Question | Example |\n|------|----------|---------|\n| Descriptive | What happened? | Cost reports |\n| Diagnostic | Why did it happen? | Variance analysis |\n| Predictive | What will happen? | Cost forecasting |\n| Prescriptive | What should we do? | VE recommendations |\n\n### Key Data Sources\n\n- Historical project data\n- Market price databases\n- Programme records\n- Claims data\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Data-driven decisions are more reliable than intuition. Build your data muscle.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Automation & Scripting (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Automation & Scripting Exercise\n\nAutomate repetitive QS tasks.\n\n---\n\n### Tasks to Automate\n\n1. **Rate lookups** — VBA/macro for rate database\n2. **Quantity aggregation** — Pivot table automation\n3. **Report generation** — Template-based reports\n4. **Data validation** — Automated checking\n\n### Example: Automated Rate Lookup\n\n```vba\nFunction GetRate(itemCode As String) As Double\n    Dim ws As Worksheet\n    Set ws = Sheets("RateDatabase")\n    GetRate = Application.VLookup(itemCode, ws.Range("A:C"), 3, False)\nEnd Function\n```\n\n### Self-Assessment\n\n- [ ] Can you create a simple macro?\n- [ ] Can you build a pivot table?\n- [ ] Can you automate report generation?\n- [ ] Do you understand when automation adds value?' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 4, Module 3: Digital Transformation Assessment
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Digital Transformation Assessment\n\nTest your digital skills across all technology modules.\n\n---\n\n### Assessment Areas\n\n1. **Measurement software** — Can you use CostX/PlanSwift?\n2. **BIM understanding** — Can you extract quantities from models?\n3. **Spreadsheet skills** — Can you build complex QS spreadsheets?\n4. **AI awareness** — Can you leverage AI tools for cost estimation?\n5. **Data analytics** — Can you analyse project data for insights?\n\n### Self-Evaluation\n\nRate yourself 1-5 in each area and identify development needs.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 5, Module 1: Digital Strategy for QS Firms
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Digital Strategy for QS Firms\n\nLeading **digital transformation** in practice.\n\n---\n\n### Strategy Framework\n\n1. **Assess** — Current digital maturity\n2. **Vision** — Target digital state\n3. **Roadmap** — Phased implementation\n4. **Execute** — Implementation\n5. **Measure** — Track benefits\n\n### Investment Priorities\n\n| Priority | Investment | Expected ROI |\n|----------|-----------|-------------|\n| Measurement tools | ₦2-5M | 30% time savings |\n| BIM capability | ₦5-10M | 40% accuracy improvement |\n| Cloud platforms | ₦1-3M | 25% collaboration improvement |\n| AI tools | ₦0.5-2M | 20% pricing speed improvement |\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Digital strategy is not about technology — it''s about improving business outcomes through technology.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: PropTech & Innovation (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## PropTech & Innovation — Case Study\n\nEmerging technologies in **construction**.\n\n---\n\n### PropTech Landscape\n\n| Category | Examples | Impact on QS |\n|----------|----------|-------------|\n| AI Estimation | QSToolkit, Buildots | Faster pricing |\n| Drones | DJI, senseFly | Site surveys |\n| IoT | Sensors, RFID | Real-time monitoring |\n| Blockchain | Smart contracts | Payment automation |\n| VR/AR | Hololens, VR | Design visualisation |\n\n### Innovation Opportunities for QS\n\n1. **AI-powered cost databases** — Real-time market rates\n2. **Automated measurement** — Computer vision for plans\n3. **Predictive analytics** — Cost and risk prediction\n4. **Smart contracts** — Automated payment processing\n\n### Case Study: QSToolkit\n\n**Innovation**: AI-powered QS platform for Nigerian market\n**Features**:\n- AI rate suggestions based on local market data\n- Automated BOQ generation from drawings\n- Cost prediction using machine learning\n- Digital measurement tools integration\n\n> **Pro Tip**: The future of QS is digital. Embrace innovation or risk obsolescence.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'digital-construction' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

-- ─── PATHWAY 7: Academic & Research Career ──────────────────

-- Level 1, Module 1: Academic Writing Basics
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Academic Writing Basics\n\nStructure and style in **academic writing** for construction research.\n\n---\n\n### Academic Paper Structure\n\n1. **Abstract** — 250-word summary\n2. **Introduction** — Background, objectives, methodology\n3. **Literature Review** — What others have found\n4. **Methodology** — How you conducted research\n5. **Results** — What you found\n6. **Discussion** — What it means\n7. **Conclusion** — Key takeaways\n8. **References** — Academic sources\n\n### Writing Style\n\n- **Formal** — No colloquialisms\n- **Objective** — Evidence-based\n- **Precise** — Clear, unambiguous\n- **Concise** — No unnecessary words\n\n### Referencing\n\n- Use Harvard or APA style consistently\n- Cite all sources\n- Maintain a reference manager (Zotero, Mendeley)\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Good academic writing is clear, concise, and evidence-based. Avoid jargon and ambiguity.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 1, Module 2: Research Methodology Intro
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Research Methodology Introduction\n\nQuantitative and **qualitative research methods**.\n\n---\n\n### Research Paradigms\n\n| Paradigm | Approach | Example |\n|----------|----------|---------|\n| Positivism | Quantitative, objective | Statistical analysis |\n| Interpretivism | Qualitative, subjective | Case studies |\n| Pragmatism | Mixed methods | Surveys + interviews |\n\n### Data Collection Methods\n\n| Method | Data Type | Strengths |\n|--------|----------|----------|\n| Survey | Quantitative | Large sample, statistical |\n| Interview | Qualitative | In-depth understanding |\n| Case study | Mixed | Real-world context |\n| Experiment | Quantitative | Causal relationships |\n\n### Research Ethics\n\n- Informed consent\n- Confidentiality\n- No harm to participants\n- Honesty in reporting\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Choose your methodology based on your research question, not personal preference.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 1 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 1: Literature Review Techniques
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Literature Review Techniques\n\nConducting and writing **literature reviews**.\n\n---\n\n### Purpose of Literature Review\n\n1. Identify what is already known\n2. Find gaps in knowledge\n3. Establish theoretical framework\n4. Justify your research\n\n### Search Strategy\n\n- Academic databases (Google Scholar, Scopus)\n- Construction-specific journals\n- Conference proceedings\n- Government reports\n\n### Review Structure\n\n1. Thematic — Organised by topic\n2. Chronological — Organised by date\n3. Methodological — Organised by method\n\n> **Pro Tip**: A good literature review is not just a summary — it critically evaluates and synthesises existing knowledge.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 2, Module 2: Data Collection Methods
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Data Collection Methods\n\nSurveys, interviews, and **case studies**.\n\n---\n\n### Survey Design\n\n1. Define objectives\n2. Design questions (closed-ended for quant, open-ended for qual)\n3. Test with pilot group\n4. Administer (online or paper)\n5. Analyse results\n\n### Interview Techniques\n\n- Semi-structured — Flexible, in-depth\n- Structured — Consistent, comparable\n- Focus groups — Group dynamics\n\n### Case Study Method\n\n1. Define case boundaries\n2. Collect multiple data sources\n3. Triangulate findings\n4. Draw conclusions\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Mixed methods (combining quant and qual) often produce the most robust research findings.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 2, Module 3: Research Design Exercise
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Research Design Exercise\n\nDesign a **research study** for a QS topic.\n\n---\n\n### Scenario\n\n**Topic**: Impact of BIM adoption on QS productivity in Nigeria\n\n### Your Task\n\n1. Formulate research questions\n2. Choose methodology (quant, qual, or mixed)\n3. Design data collection instruments\n4. Plan sampling strategy\n5. Outline analysis approach\n\n### Expected Deliverable\n\nA 2-page research proposal including:\n- Research questions\n- Methodology justification\n- Data collection plan\n- Timeline\n- Ethical considerations\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Clarity of research questions | 25% |\n| Methodology appropriateness | 30% |\n| Feasibility | 25% |\n| Presentation | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 2 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 3, Module 1: Statistical Analysis for QS
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Statistical Analysis for QS\n\nUsing statistics in **construction research**.\n\n---\n\n### Common Statistical Tests\n\n| Test | Use Case | Data Type |\n|------|----------|-----------|\n| T-test | Compare two groups | Continuous |\n| ANOVA | Compare multiple groups | Continuous |\n| Chi-square | Test associations | Categorical |\n| Regression | Predict relationships | Continuous |\n\n### Software Options\n\n- SPSS — Most common in academia\n- R — Free, powerful\n- Python — Growing in construction research\n- Excel — Basic analysis\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Understanding statistics helps you evaluate research claims and make data-driven decisions.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 3, Module 2: Thesis/Dissertation Planning
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Thesis/Dissertation Planning\n\nStructuring a **research thesis**.\n\n---\n\n### Thesis Structure\n\n1. Introduction (10%)\n2. Literature Review (25%)\n3. Methodology (15%)\n4. Results (20%)\n5. Discussion (20%)\n6. Conclusion (10%)\n\n### Timeline\n\n| Phase | Duration |\n|-------|----------|\n| Proposal | 1 month |\n| Literature review | 2-3 months |\n| Data collection | 2-3 months |\n| Analysis | 1-2 months |\n| Writing | 2-3 months |\n| Revision | 1 month |\n\n### Tips for Success\n\n1. Start with a clear research question\n2. Set realistic timelines\n3. Meet with supervisor regularly\n4. Write as you go — don''t leave it all to the end\n5. Reference consistently\n\n> **Pro Tip**: A good thesis is not about having brilliant ideas — it''s about systematic, rigorous research.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 3, Module 3: Research Proposal Case Study
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Research Proposal Case Study\n\nDevelop a **research proposal** on a QS topic.\n\n---\n\n### Topic: Cost Overruns in Nigerian Public Construction Projects\n\n### Proposal Elements\n\n1. **Title**: An Analysis of Cost Overrun Causes in Nigerian Public Construction Projects\n2. **Background**: Cost overruns average 30-50% in Nigerian public projects\n3. **Objectives**: Identify main causes, assess impact, propose mitigation\n4. **Methodology**: Mixed methods — survey of 200 QS professionals + 10 case studies\n5. **Expected outcomes**: Framework for cost overrun prevention\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Research relevance | 25% |\n| Methodology rigor | 30% |\n| Feasibility | 25% |\n| Academic quality | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 3 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 4, Module 1: Journal Publication Guide
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Journal Publication Guide\n\nPublishing research in **academic journals**.\n\n---\n\n### Publication Process\n\n1. **Write** — Prepare manuscript\n2. **Select journal** — Match scope and impact\n3. **Submit** — Follow author guidelines\n4. **Peer review** — Revise based on feedback\n5. **Acceptance** — Final revisions\n6. **Publication** — Online and print\n\n### Nigerian Construction Journals\n\n- Nigerian Journal of Technology\n- Journal of Engineering and Applied Sciences\n- Building and Construction Journal\n\n### International Journals\n\n- Construction Management and Economics\n- Engineering, Construction and Architectural Management\n- International Journal of Construction Management\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Start by presenting at conferences before targeting journals. Conference papers are easier to publish.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 4, Module 2: Conference Presentation Skills (Exercise)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Conference Presentation Exercise\n\nPrepare and deliver an **academic presentation**.\n\n---\n\n### Task\n\nPrepare a 15-minute presentation on your research topic.\n\n### Presentation Structure\n\n1. **Hook** — Start with a compelling fact or question\n2. **Context** — Background and significance\n3. **Methodology** — How you conducted research\n4. **Key findings** — 3-4 main results\n5. **Implications** — What it means for practice\n6. **Conclusion** — Summary and future work\n\n### Presentation Tips\n\n1. Use visual aids — charts, diagrams\n2. Limit text on slides\n3. Practice timing\n4. Prepare for questions\n5. Be confident and engaging\n\n### Assessment Criteria\n\n| Criterion | Weight |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Content quality | 30% |\n| Presentation skills | 30% |\n| Visual aids | 20% |\n| Q&A handling | 20% |' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 2;

-- Level 4, Module 3: Academic Career Assessment
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Academic Career Assessment\n\nTest your **research skills** across all academic modules.\n\n---\n\n### Assessment Areas\n\n1. **Research design** — Can you formulate research questions?\n2. **Methodology** — Can you choose appropriate methods?\n3. **Data analysis** — Can you analyse quantitative/qualitative data?\n4. **Writing** — Can you write academic papers?\n5. **Presentation** — Can you present research effectively?\n\n### Self-Evaluation\n\nRate yourself 1-5 in each area and identify development needs.\n\n### Next Steps\n\n- Identify 2-3 development areas\n- Create a learning plan\n- Seek mentorship from experienced researchers' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 4 AND order_index = 3;

-- Level 5, Module 1: Grant Writing & Funding
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Grant Writing & Funding\n\nSecuring **research funding** and grants.\n\n---\n\n### Funding Sources\n\n| Source | Type | Typical Amount |\n|--------|------|----------------|\n| TETFund | Nigerian government | ₦5-20M |\n| British Council | International | £10,000-50,000 |\n| World Bank | Development research | $50,000-200,000 |\n| NIQS | Professional body | ₦1-5M |\n\n### Grant Proposal Structure\n\n1. Executive summary\n2. Problem statement\n3. Objectives and methodology\n4. Expected outcomes\n5. Budget and timeline\n6. Team qualifications\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Grant writing is a skill that improves with practice. Start with small grants and build up.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 1;

-- Level 5, Module 2: Supervision & Mentoring (Case Study)
UPDATE academy_modules SET content = E'## Supervision & Mentoring — Case Study\n\nGuiding the **next generation** of researchers.\n\n---\n\n### Supervision Styles\n\n| Style | Description | When to Use |\n|-------|-------------|-------------|\n| Directive | Provide clear guidance | New researchers |\n| Facilitative | Enable discovery | Intermediate |\n| Delegative | Minimal intervention | Advanced |\n\n### Mentoring Approach\n\n1. **Goal setting** — Clear objectives\n2. **Regular meetings** — Structured check-ins\n3. **Feedback** — Constructive, timely\n4. **Network building** — Introductions and connections\n\n### Common Supervision Challenges\n\n1. Student motivation\n2. Research scope creep\n3. Writing quality\n4. Time management\n5. Intellectual property\n\n> **Pro Tip**: Good supervision is about guiding, not controlling. Help students develop their own research identity.' WHERE pathway_slug = 'academic-research' AND level = 5 AND order_index = 2;

